# Lab 01 — Dialogue Summarization with FLAN-T5

# Overview
----------------------------------------------------
This lab explores dialogue summarization using the FLAN-T5 model and the DialogSum dataset.

The main goal was to understand how different prompting strategies affect the quality of generated summaries without updating the model weights.
----------------------------------------------------
## Topics Covered

- Dialogue summarization
- Prompt engineering
- Zero-shot inference
- One-shot inference
- Few-shot inference
- Instruction-style prompting
- Generation parameters
- Temperature
- Maximum output tokens
- Context window limitations
-------------------------------------------------------------
## Tools and Libraries

- Python
- Google Colab
- Hugging Face Transformers
- Hugging Face Datasets
- PyTorch
- FLAN-T5
- DialogSum dataset
-----------------------------------------------------------
## What I Did

In this lab, I loaded a pre-trained FLAN-T5 model and used it to summarize conversations from the DialogSum dataset.

I tested different inference strategies:

- No prompt engineering
- Zero-shot prompting
- One-shot prompting
- Few-shot prompting
- Instruction-style prompts

I also experimented with generation parameters such as `temperature`, `do_sample`, and `max_new_tokens` to observe how they affect the model output.
---------------------------------------------------------------
## Key Results

The model performed poorly when no clear instruction was provided. The generated output improved when the prompt included a direct summarization instruction.

One-shot and few-shot prompting helped guide the model with examples, but too many examples caused context length limitations. This showed the importance of balancing prompt quality with the model's context window.

Temperature also affected the output. Lower temperatures produced more conservative and stable responses, while higher temperatures created more varied but sometimes less precise summaries.
----------------------------------------------------------------
## Key Learning

This lab showed that prompt design has a major impact on LLM behavior. Even without fine-tuning, a well-structured prompt can significantly improve the quality of the generated response.

I also learned that smaller models can struggle with one-shot and few-shot inference when the task becomes complex or the prompt becomes too long.
------------------------------------------------------------------
## Professional Takeaway

This lab helped me understand how prompt engineering can be used to guide LLMs toward better outputs before applying more advanced techniques such as fine-tuning, PEFT, or reinforcement learning.
-----------------------------------------------------------------
## Notes

This notebook was completed as part of my Generative AI learning path. The focus was educational: understanding how FLAN-T5 responds to different prompt structures and generation settings.
